# ── False positives — npm overrides in demo/ ─────────────────────────────────
#
# Trivy scans package.json files nested inside node_modules (the dependencies
# declared by each installed package). This causes it to report the version
# *required* by a transitive dep's package.json rather than the version
# *actually installed* (which is patched via demo/package.json overrides).
#
# All packages below are pinned to their patched versions via `overrides` in
# demo/package.json. The actual installed versions are not vulnerable.

# cross-spawn: installed 7.0.6 (fix), Trivy finds 7.0.3 in nested package.json
CVE-2024-21538

# glob: not installed in demo/node_modules (no direct or indirect dependency)
CVE-2025-64756

# minimatch: installed 9.0.9 (fix), Trivy finds 9.0.5 in nested package.json
CVE-2026-26996
CVE-2026-27903
CVE-2026-27904

# tar: not installed in demo/node_modules (no direct or indirect dependency)
CVE-2026-23745
CVE-2026-23950
CVE-2026-24842
CVE-2026-26960
CVE-2026-29786
CVE-2026-31802

# ── Discharged ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# CVE-2026-48815 (sigstore in the base image's bundled npm) used to be
# suppressed here, deferred to "a future base-image bump" because the fix
# needed npm >= 12 and the base was node 20. The base is node 26 now and the
# Dockerfile installs npm 12 explicitly, so the deferral is discharged and the
# entry is gone rather than left to rot.
#
# As of the 2.2.6 scan, a fresh-database Trivy run reports zero HIGH/CRITICAL
# even with this file empty of that entry. The suppressions above are kept
# because they cover a recurring Trivy behaviour (reading versions from nested
# package.json files) rather than a one-off, so they can resurface at any DB
# update. Anything that can be fixed is fixed, not suppressed.
